segments.text: Things he did was establish, for me, it was Wednesday morning meetings.
Every other week, I had an audience with him.
Now, either of us could call and cancel, and sometimes did, but not too often.
And for an hour, I had his complete ear.
We'd spend three or four minutes talking about what was on his mind, and then the rest of the time was mine.
And the answer to the question is yes, very definitely yes.
Back to your own style, a while ago I meant to ask and I think I interrupted myself.
As department head, how much did you feel bound, I'd say it's in a faculty review, a promotion, a tenure, or an appointment, how much did you feel bound by the majority opinion of the department?
compared to your own evaluation?
For the most part, I felt the faculty's will ought to be served, but I wasn't afraid if there was...
I only recall one time going against the faculty in a tenure decision, and of course I sent both recommendations forward, but
Was yours negative compared to theirs?
No, mine was positive and theirs was negative.
Okay.
In that particular instance, it could have gone the other way.
What I made my faculty a promise with, one good example is new faculty hires.
A promise I made them was that I would not hire someone that they didn't want, but I would not allow them to hire someone that I didn't want.
And that worked pretty well in most things we dealt with.
I don't, if I erred, I erred on the side of bringing the faculty in too much.
I think they got weary of that toward the end.
And I probably didn't use good judgment in some cases.
During your years as department head, now in looking back, did the department miss any opportunities?
We missed a big one right at the end of my tenure.
I think, time will tell.
We had an opportunity to develop a biomechanics lab.
We had biomechanics as a specialty, but we didn't have a very good lab.
We had an excellent exercise physiology lab.
We had a very good motor learning lab.
We had a chance to develop biomechanics, and I thought we should have done that.
If we had done that, we'd be studying in a very scientific way the most efficient way
of performing a sports skill, and might even could have landed one of the Olympic training centers on this campus.
But the exercise physiology people at that time saw that as a threat.
Because it was going to take some money to do that.
That equipment is not cheap.
And they saw that as money siphoning away from them.
The motor learning felt the same way.
And that was a case where the faculty carried the day.
I didn't think that was a decision that needed to be unilaterally made.
It was one that if enough people were against it, it would fail.
I think we missed the boat there.
I think we really should have done that.
But time will tell, because what we have done instead is our exercise physiology program is twice as large now as it was.
We have the only two distinguished professors in the College of Education are both in physical education, the current department head and Jack Wilmore, who was department head last year.
That program I think very quickly will be, we're talking about top tens, I think very quickly they will be named among the top ten in the country and maybe in the top four or five.
Now, in terms of Vision 2020, that's the right track to take.
In terms of serving the people of Texas, I'm not so sure.
Your health was what caused you to need to decide to step
away from being department head, I presume.
Well, no, actually not.
I had decided that I was going to do that because I was reaching the point where I felt like
Well, I lost my leader.
Corrigan had stepped down as dean.
And he had been my, let's see, one, two, three, my fourth dean.
And as you know, you can only serve so many masters that way.
Because every one of them changes a little, and that forces you to change your direction a little.
And you tend to lose some of your consistency, I think.
That had a lot to do with it.
The other was I was growing tired.
I'd been there a while, and I think they were a little tired of me too.
And I enjoyed teaching, and I wanted to get back to that.
I had already made the decision to retire, not retire, but to resign from the department of his job, and in fact had resigned before I was diagnosed with heart disease.
And so what did you start doing, and what were your goals then as a full-time faculty member?
I requested a study leave and was granted that.
And so I went down to Baylor College of Medicine

I have a good friend down that I had been working with all these years and took some courses there and also at the UT School of Public Health to try to recover my discipline a little because I obviously had lost my discipline by then.

I came back and my goal was to spend the first year getting my classes laid out so that I felt comfortable then and then my second year I was going to focus on establishing a research agenda and I had full plans to
to become a working active member of the faculty again.
Because when I became a department head, I thought I was near the cutting edge of my field.
I wanted to get back somewhere then.
I made the first year all right, but it was in that first year that my wife was diagnosed with breast cancer and then I was diagnosed with heart disease.
I'm afraid I didn't meet that latter goal because by then I was thinking pretty seriously about it was time to start thinking about retiring.
But you're still full-time right now?
I'm still full-time right now.
And what are you working on?
Well, this year, for the first year I haven't taught.
I've been teaching a full load until this year.
This year I bought my teaching time out with a chair.
And what I'm attempting to do is get ready to turn loose the camp because that still is, I think, an important part of our department.
I'm on the board of trustees for the Reed Youth Charities.
And Mrs. Reed would like for me to continue to be the overseer of the camp even after retirement.
And I may very well come back.
In fact, the plan is to come back 25 percent of the time and do that.
But this year what I've tried to do is locate some of our campers.
We don't have real good follow-up work on where those youngsters are.
Each one of them that go to that camp are guaranteed a scholarship to A&M.
We haven't been moderately successful.
They're all at-risk kids, and getting them in the university is real difficult.
We've only had seven or eight or nine all the time we worked.
But where are the rest of them?
I'm convinced that we've done some good with those youngsters, but where are they now?
So I've been trying to do some follow-up with them.
And then also establish some relationship with school districts where they will help us identify youngsters who are at risk that we can give that same experience to.
So I've been doing most of that this year.
I had enough funds in the chair to do it once.
I couldn't do that more than once.
Of your almost 30 years here,

To what administrators, deans, vice presidents, or provosts, presidents, chancellors, I'm not going to ask the negative, to which administrators would you give the highest marks for their leadership here at A&M?
Well, I've always already said that Jack Williams was my hero, and I'll stick by that.
I think he was outstanding.
But he, in all honesty, he didn't have a lot of effect on me.
other than peripherally, the president that,
I knew Jarvis Miller very well.

His daughter and my daughter played in the orchestra, the Rises Valley Orchestra, and I was with him on a trip to see our girls play the week before he was named president the next week, and I didn't have a clue that was going to happen.
So I knew him well, but I have to say Frank Vandiver probably was the next president that I
was most impacted by.
He had a tumultuous administration, but gosh, he was good to work with.
You recall the days when seniors didn't have to take final tests.
The faculty senate decided to dig their heels in, and we were going to change this.
And we went to his office.
to hear the words spoken by him that it ain't gonna fly.
And we were able to sit there and work out and negotiate a compromise.
that when we hit upon it, it was almost like he knew this is what should happen, but he was waiting for us to say it and walked away from there feeling real good about it.
And in fact, we got it done.
He was a faculty member's department president, I think.
I think he never was comfortable being a president.
He was still a faculty member.
So from that point of view, those were the two that I thought the most of.
I really only worked...
a reasonable time with two deans, Hubert when I was a faculty member and then later on as department head.
Lembacher, Phil Lembacher was acting for a year and he was very, very helpful because I was a brand new department head, didn't know, come here from Sycam and he helped me an awful lot.
But then Corrigan would have to be my pick there.
I worked with Chris Borman as an acting dean for a while.
And then I only served one year under Jane Stallings.
So at the dean's level, I thought that was, Cargan would be my pick.

I only worked for one department head here, and that was, well, no, actually, Carl Landis was the department head, but I worked with Bob Armstrong, who's the current department head, and Jack Wilmore, but it was after I had been in that role, and they pretty well left me alone, and I didn't,
I didn't and I tried to stay out of their way.
So I have to say in retrospect that Carl was really fun to work for and that's surprising me that I can say that today because my first three or four years I wouldn't have told you that at all.
Are there other people related to your A&M experience if they could be brought into this room that you would want to express appreciation to?
Oh, gosh, yes.
Brian Cole was really helpful.
Particularly after I became department head, he was helpful.
Because he was then the assistant.
He was then assistant to the dean and became, before I left the office, he became associate dean and took Limbacher's position.
He was really good to work with.
And Cargan was wise enough to turn a lot of things over to him.
That's in the college level.
I'll always appreciate Chris Borman, because he took a thankless job and did it.
I don't think we were, as a university, was quite straight with him, because he took the acting dean's job thinking he had a chance to be dean, and really didn't have a chance.
In the upper administration, Chuck McCandless was outstanding.
Of course, he understood us.
I loved that guy like a brother almost, and he was neat.
I've forgotten who was provost that went to Iowa State.
It may have been your friend that called you about the basketball club.
Oh, no, no.
Former dean of geosciences.
Right, that's right.
I really liked him an awful lot.
You were gone by the time he came aboard, weren't you?
He did a very nice job.
Let's see, some goofy moments in your A&M experience?
I took the liberty of trying to think of a few of those.
One was, remember Howard Vestal?
Sure.
Howard Vestal erected a stop sign in the middle of a block right across from Rudder Tower.
This was after you, I think you may have been in Missouri at that time, but he came out of his office one day
and almost got hit by a car, came back the next day and ruled that they were going to put a stop sign up.
And he had a stop sign right in the middle of that intersection where he crossed.
And cars would .
And 30 minutes after he retired, that stop sign came down.
That's a good one.
I thought that was outstanding.
Pranks that anybody ever played on the department head while you were the department head?
I don't know whether it was a prank or not, but God played a prank on us.
My first year as department head, the snow melted on Mount Aggie.
I think you were still here then.
Well, I know what Mount Aggie was.
Yeah, okay.
We had AstroTurf on Mount Aggie, and Carl Landis retired, but one of the last things he did was buy something called SNO something.
I forgot what it was.
Snow Flow or something like that.
It was a black surface.
It had prongs sticking up on it, and the kids really liked it.
The teachers liked it because it really would give you the feel of edging in snow.
The only problem is when the weather got the slightest bit cool that fall, that brittle, and they'd pop off just like machines.
And so I got a phone call.
Chip, what's Chip's name, works down at the TV station, one of the radio stations in town, Chip Howard.
Chip Howard wanted to interview me.
And, of course, I'd only been on the job just a few weeks, and I thought,
Oh, Lord, I am going to embarrass the whole university.
And what he wanted to envy me about was the snow that melted on Mount Aggie.
And I went to great detail to explain to him that we were careful not to waste the university's money.
I surely thought he was on a witch hunt when he came.
Probably the worst thing that happened to me
It happened in 1986.
We had a teacher, she's still on our faculty, a very fine teacher.
And she taught outdoor, what we called outdoor education.
And in that program was a weekend camping trip where they would go out to the wilderness someplace.
And in this case, they went to Enchanted Rock out near Kerrville and would rock climb at the backside of that rock.
And she did some really neat things with those youngsters.
That was the safest thing they did was rock climbing, in fact.
But she did some really neat things with those kids and we have a ropes course that she developed and a lot of business executives go through that building team and that kind of thing.
But she had gone by automobile and she had six people in a car and on the way back,

Out there where the east loop joins 21, she was ahead of this particular, I don't know if there's a car ahead of them or not, but she was ahead of one car and she exited on to the sixth loop and she said she looked in the rearview mirror and saw the other car missed the turn and remarked did they miss the turn.

What they did was they went down another few blocks and realized they'd missed the turn, pulled over, and then made a U-turn right in front of a tractor truck, and it killed five of those kids, and one of them was Robert Walker's son, Richard.
I'm telling you, I'm still fragile about that.
It's the worst thing that can happen to anyone.
To a lesser degree, I understood what
President Bowen was going through with the bonfire thing.
It just eats your guts right out.
And I don't think I ever recovered from that totally.
It's something I remember, but I don't want to remember it.
Yes.
And Bob Walker and his wife Joanne were rocks.
I mean, just strong, strong faith.
That's right.
Absolutely.
All right, now I'm just about out of questions.
What have we left out that we should have?
Well, I think maybe you gave me a chance to say about everything I noticed.
You were talking about Mac Prescott a while ago.
I was thinking about some things.
Everybody who lives in the administration, I think, has some one-liners that are really good.
You were always good at this.
Your sense of humor was, I think, kept you apart.
Mac Prescott was famous for saying, give me patience and give it to me now.
And I'm humble and proud of it.
And I guess I picked up some little things like that from nearly everybody who sat in that office.
I remember
Oh, who was the president that preceded Bowen?
I'm blocking his name.
Bill Mobley?
Bill Mobley.
Bill Mobley retired and John Coles retired three days before him and three days after him.
And at John Coles' retirement reception, Bill Mobley said, I promised myself that I would retire three days before John Coles.
I thought that was good.
I believe we've, okay, let me then appoint you as a consultant.
Let's make believe that you have now been recruited to advise the department and the college about what they're, what they should be trying to do next.
What advice would you give to the department
in the College of Education as they are looking toward the future?
I think from the college's point of view, they're in a real difficult situation.
Somewhere along the way,
we decided that colleges of education were the cause of poor teaching that goes on in public schools and poor education that goes on there.
And consequently, colleges of education are just hanging on by their fingertips.
And as a result of that, they are doing some things that they might not ought to be doing.
I wouldn't expect anybody to take this advice, but I think it's what colleges ought to do, is they shouldn't sell their souls in order to survive.
If they can't survive doing what they are designed to do, then fold.
Just go away.
Now, that's contrary to what human nature is.
But I think if we aren't careful,
we'll try to do some things we shouldn't be doing, and we wind up not doing those well and getting in trouble.
If I were going to advise the department, a lot of it goes back to what you and I have already talked about.
I really think that we are much, much overemphasizing the exercise physiology component.
They don't have a constituency.
They're very good at what they're doing.
They're conducting very good research.
And as I said, we have the only two distinguished professors in the entire college.
And they are good.
I think their research would stand up with anybody's.
But who are they doing it for?
They can't, they don't have a constituency.
They're doing it for the sake of reporting it in journals of which other exercise physiologists will read and do research and report to other exercise physiologists.
And that pyramid's going to topple one of these days.
We're, more and more we're charging students who are using the university
We're putting more and more of the burden of paying for the university on them, less and less on the state.
And the more we do that, the more critical the parents who are paying for the education are going to be.
And one day they're going to look and say, what are we getting for our money?
And I'm of the opinion right now that it's the worst investment they make, based on what, as an insider in the university, I think it's one of the worst investments they make.
And that breaks my heart to say that.
I wish I didn't believe that.
I wish it weren't true.
And hopefully it isn't true, but it sure feels that way.
So I'd say to our department, we need to determine who our constituencies are and try to address their needs better than what we're doing right now.
All right.
Let's make believe someone walks up and gives you a check for a million dollars with one condition.
You must pass it on to Texas A&M, but you've got to decide the use of that money.
If you could make a truly meaningful gift to this institution, for what purpose would you give that?
There's just a bunch of them, obviously.
You're asking me now to be magnanimous, and I don't know if I could be.
Well, I guess what I think, I don't know if this would be the answer I'd give or not, but it addresses a need that's consistent with what I just said.
The cost of going to school is greater now than it's ever been, and I fear that a lot of people are being cut out now
for reasons that they never were cut out before.
When I came to school, money was not going to keep me from going to college.
My ability and willingness to study might, but I could probably make it.
I could sell eggs and make it.
But that's not true anymore.
So I guess I would encourage that person to put them into scholarships that students could.
What kind of students would you want to receive these scholarships?
Well, I don't think I would, again, this is consistent with what my beliefs is, I wouldn't want them to become the elite student.
I wouldn't want them to go to the elite student.
To the elite?
Yeah.
You mean elite in?
Elite in terms of having to be the very top best students you can get your hands on.
I think when all your scholarships are restricted to just that level of student,
Again, we're leaving a lot of people out.
Would this be on the basis of need?
Yes, yes.
What about their major?
Well, I don't know if I would want to... Obviously, I'd be biased.
I'd want...
us to get the whole million dollars.
But I don't think it should.
I think the need is going to be across the board.
You could make the case that maybe some fields are attracting people who can pay their way.
But I think there are people who can go into those fields who can't pay their way.
There's no question that we've got a dichotomy going on in our society.
The rich are getting richer, and the poor are getting poorer.
And I don't think it's all because of the rich being so selfish and jealous.
I think some of it is the way we're running our universities.
We've become so elite until all of us want to teach the very best, and we want to shoot the rest.
And was it Jefferson who said, you could tell me, to expect a country to be uneducated and free is to expect what never was and never will be?
We're leaving a lot of people out.
And A&M is contributing to that, because every time we pass a $50 a semester fee, someone else is not coming to school because of it.
Last question.
What feelings do you carry in your heart for this institution now?
Oh, I love it.
I love it.
I've always fallen in love with every institution I've ever worked in.
I don't know whether my dad taught me this or where I got it, but I've never worked at a place I didn't love.
It doesn't take me very long to fall in love, but A&M is a special place.
I tell my kids when I talk regularly that there's two or three things I've learned about them.
One is they are unique.
To say that there's a spirit of Aggieland is to belie the spirit of other universities.
Every university has a spirit.
But this is a very distinct spirit.
And what I say to them is, you don't know how good you are.
I have found that they know how to play.
And they can play as good as any of them.
But they know when to stop playing and start working.
And they do it better than any group I've ever been associated with.
For a non-aggie, I bleed maroon and white pretty severely.
It's a great place.
